markdown# Day 3 — Recursion on Arrays

Today was the third day of recursion. The first two days I learned
what recursion is and how it works. Today I actually used recursion
on arrays and understood how to think through each problem step by step.

---

## What I Practiced Today

All three problems today were about arrays. The idea was the same
in every problem — visit one element at a time, check a condition,
and move to the next index recursively.

---

## The Pattern I Learned Today

Every array recursion problem follows this exact structure:

```python
def do_something(arr, i=0):
    if i == len(arr):        # base case — fell off the end
        return ___           # return 0 or False or True

    if condition(arr[i]):    # check current element only
        return ___ + do_something(arr, i+1)

    return do_something(arr, i+1)   # skip and move forward
```

Once I understood this pattern all three problems became easier.
I just had to change the condition in the middle.

---

## Problem 1 — Count Elements Greater Than X

### What the problem asks

Given an array and a number x, count how many elements
are greater than x using recursion.
count_greater([1, 5, 3, 7, 2], 3) → 2
count_greater([1, 2, 3], 5)       → 0
count_greater([6, 7, 8], 5)       → 3

### What I understood

At first I was thinking about the whole array at once. That was
wrong. Recursion thinks about one element at a time. So at each
step I only ask one question — is arr[i] greater than x? If yes
count it. If no skip it. Then move to the next index.

### Code

```python
def count_greater(arr, x, i=0):
    if i == len(arr):
        return 0

    if arr[i] > x:
        return 1 + count_greater(arr, x, i+1)

    return count_greater(arr, x, i+1)
```

### Dry run — count_greater([1, 5, 3, 7, 2], 3)
i=0 → arr[0]=1, 1>3? No  → skip → i=1
i=1 → arr[1]=5, 5>3? Yes → 1 + → i=2
i=2 → arr[2]=3, 3>3? No  → skip → i=3
i=3 → arr[3]=7, 7>3? Yes → 1 + → i=4
i=4 → arr[4]=2, 2>3? No  → skip → i=5
i=5 → WALL → return 0
Coming back up
1 + 0 = 1
1 + 1 = 2 ✅

### Complexity

Time  : O(n) — visits every element once  
Space : O(n) — n frames on call stack

### Mistake I made

I tried to write `if x not in arr` which checks the whole array
at once. That is not how recursion works. Recursion checks one
element at a time using the index i. I have to stop thinking about
the whole array and focus on arr[i] only.

