## Problem 2 — Find Minimum in Array

### What the problem asks

Find the smallest element in the array using recursion.
find_min([3, 1, 7, 2, 9]) → 1
find_min([5, 5, 5])        → 5
find_min([10])             → 10

### What I understood

The base case here is different. Instead of checking
`i == len(arr)` I check `i == len(arr) - 1`. That means I reached
the last element. The last element has nothing to compare with so
I return it directly as the minimum.

Then I compare current element with the minimum of the rest and
return whichever is smaller.

### Code

```python
def find_min(arr, i=0):
    if i == len(arr) - 1:
        return arr[i]

    min_of_rest = find_min(arr, i+1)

    if arr[i] < min_of_rest:
        return arr[i]
    else:
        return min_of_rest
```

### Dry run — find_min([3, 1, 7])
Going down
find_min(i=0) → find_min(i=1)
find_min(i=1) → find_min(i=2)
find_min(i=2) → last element → return 7
Coming back up
i=1 → 1 < 7? Yes → return 1
i=0 → 3 < 1? No  → return 1 ✅

### Complexity

Time  : O(n) — visits every element once  
Space : O(n) — n frames on call stack

### Mistake I made

In the base case I wrote `return 1` instead of `return arr[i]`.
That was wrong because I was hardcoding a value instead of
returning the actual last element. The base case should always
return the real answer for the smallest input, not a hardcoded
number.

