## Problem 3 — Find Maximum in Array

### What the problem asks

Find the largest element in the array using recursion.
find_max([3, 1, 7, 2, 9]) → 9
find_max([5, 5, 5])        → 5
find_max([10])             → 10

### What I understood

This is exactly the same as find_min. Only one thing changes.
The condition flips from less than to greater than. That is the
only difference. Once I saw this pattern it clicked immediately.

### Code

```python
def find_max(arr, i=0):
    if i == len(arr) - 1:
        return arr[i]

    max_of_rest = find_max(arr, i+1)

    if arr[i] > max_of_rest:
        return arr[i]
    else:
        return max_of_rest
```

### Dry run — find_max([3, 1, 7])
Going down
find_max(i=0) → find_max(i=1)
find_max(i=1) → find_max(i=2)
find_max(i=2) → last element → return 7
Coming back up
i=1 → 1 > 7? No  → return 7
i=0 → 3 > 7? No  → return 7 ✅

### Complexity

Time  : O(n) — visits every element once  
Space : O(n) — n frames on call stack

### Find Min vs Find Max — only one thing changes
find_min → if arr[i] < min_of_rest
find_max → if arr[i] > max_of_rest

Everything else is identical.

---

## The Big Lesson From Today

At the start of Day 3 I was confused about what
`if i == len(arr)` means. Now I understand it completely.

When i reaches len(arr) it means we have gone past the last
valid index. The array only has indexes 0 to len(arr)-1. So
index len(arr) does not exist. This check acts like a wall that
stops us from going out of bounds.

For find_min and find_max the wall is at len(arr)-1 because
we compare arr[i] with arr[i+1]. So we stop one step earlier.

---

## What I Will Remember Forever
if i == len(arr)     → fell off the end → return 0 or False
if i == len(arr)-1   → last element → return arr[i]
Never hardcode base case values
Always return the actual answer for smallest input

